Americas
--------
[1] USA (source and genotype)
Date: Fri 6 Jun 2014
Source: Measles -- United States, 1 Jan-23 May 2014, MMWR Weekly 63(22);496-499 [extract, edited - Mod.CP]
http://www.cdc.gov/mmwr/preview/mmwrhtml/mm6322a4.htm?s_cid=mm6322a4_w


Origin and genotypes measles viruses strains imported in the USA
----------------------------------------------------------------
Of the 288 measles cases, 280 (97 percent) were associated with importations from at least 18 countries. The source of measles acquisition could not be identified for 8 (3 percent) cases. 45 direct importations (40 US residents returning from abroad and 5 foreign visitors) have been reported. Almost half (22 [49 percent]) of these importations were travelers returning from the Philippines, where a large outbreak has been occurring since October 2013. Imported cases were also associated with travel from other countries in the World Health Organization (WHO) Western Pacific Region (7 cases), as well as countries in the WHO South-East Asia (8), European (4), Americas (3), and Eastern Mediterranean (1) regions. Measles genotype information was obtained from 103 (36 percent) of the 288 measles cases. Four measles virus genotypes were identified: B3 (67 cases), D9 (23), D8 (12), and H1, as follows:

Country of origin / Measles virus genotype

Pakistan / B3
Dublin, Germany, England / B3
France, Belgium / D8
Republic of Georgia / B3
Brazil / B3
Chile / D8
India / D8
China / H1
Micronesia / B3
Philippies / B3, D9
Saipan (Marianna Islands) / B3
Singapore / D8
Viet Nam / D8

Viruses also originated from Indonesia, the Netherlands, South Korea and Thailand, but the genotypes were not determined.

Genotype was determined based on methodology described in the WHO measles virus nomenclature 2012 update: Wkly Epidemiol Rec 2012;87:73-80. Genotypes listed are those identified in a sample from the imported case or from a case that is epidemiologically linked to that importation.

