[4] USA (Kansas)
Date: Tue 24 June 2014
Source: The Wichita Eagle [summ., edited - Mod.CP]
http://www.kansas.com/2014/06/24/3523983/wichita-area-health-officials.html


So far in 2014, the CDC has reported 514 cases in 20 states, with 16 outbreaks representing 87 percent of the reported cases this year. During most years since 2000, fewer than 100 measles cases have been reported in the US.

Earlier this month [June 2014], 3 cases were confirmed in Johnson County [Kansas]. The Kansas City metro area has 27 confirmed cases, according to the communications director for the Kansas Department of Health and Environment. "We hope we don't see a widespread outbreak in the state," said Charlie Hunt, state epidemiologist for KDHE. "That would be an unfortunate circumstance. Measles can cause complications like ear infections and pneumonia. For every 1000 children with the disease in the US, 1 or 2 will die, according to the CDC. Those most at risk for complications are children under 5, adults over 20, those with compromised immune systems and pregnant women, according to the CDC.

[Byline: Kelsey Ryan]

--
