[5] USA (Washington)
Date: Thu 26 Jun 2014
Source: Bothell Reporter [summ., edited - Mod.CP]
http://www.bothell-reporter.com/news/264811961.html


Local public health officials are investigating 8 confirmed cases of measles among members of the same extended family in south King County, and a single suspected case in Pierce County [Washington state]. These cases are linked to another case who returned to the United States from the Pacific Islands on [26 May 2014] with measles. Given the unfolding investigation and uncertainty about places where the people with measles may have visited, anyone residing in south King County or Pierce County should:
- be aware that measles cases are occurring in the community,
- be up to date on measles vaccine,
- and follow the recommendations below if they develop symptoms of measles

Known public exposures occurred at several MultiCare healthcare facilities where the infected individuals were treated, including a hospital in Tacoma [Pierce County, Washington]. Details about these exposures will be updated regularly at the MultiCare website. These medical facilities are directly contacting persons who were present -- clients, visitors, and staff -- during the times of potential exposure.

Anyone who lives or works in south King County should be alert for an illness with fever or illness with an unexplained rash, for at least the next 3 weeks. A combination of these signs or symptoms is a strong indicator of measles: fever, rash, cough, and red, watery eyes. Members of the south King County household were unvaccinated because they were too young to receive the vaccine or simply missed their vaccinations. Public Health-Seattle & King County is working closely with a community from Micronesia connected to the outbreak, and is conducting extensive outreach to ensure as many people as possible in this community are vaccinated.

