[7] Philippines (Cebu)
Date: Thu 26 Jun 2014
Source: Sun Star, Cebu [summ., edited - Mod.CP]
http://www.sunstar.com.ph/cebu/local-news/2014/06/26/measles-outbreak-cpdrc-350470


Some 43 inmates at the Cebu Provincial and Rehabilitation Canter (CPDRC) are displaying measles-like symptoms, prompting the Regional Epidemiological Surveillance Unit (Resu 7) to monitor their condition. The Director of Resu 7 said there were initially 22 cases last week [week ending 22 Jun 2014]. He considered the sudden jump to be of epidemic proportion. He said they've confined those whom they suspect of having measles in separate cells to keep them away from healthy inmates.

The Director said 11 inmates who initially gave blood samples all tested positive for measles. He said those with fever were given supportive treatment: medicine for fever and vitamin A, as measles depletes the patient's vitamin supply, causing poor eyesight. If left untreated, he said, the disease might damage the eyesight permanently. Measles, he said, may also lead to pneumonia. The Director blamed jail visitors for infecting the inmates, adding that congestion and poor ventilation had helped spread the virus. The CPDRC is home to 1971 inmates.

[Byline: Oscar C. Pineda]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail from HealthMap Alerts
<promed@promedmail.org>

[The WHO recommends that all children (and socially deprived adults) in developing countries diagnosed with measles should receive 2 doses of vitamin A supplements, given 24 hours apart. This treatment restores low vitamin A levels during measles that occur even in well-nourished individuals and can help prevent eye damage and blindness. Vitamin A supplements have been shown to reduce the number of deaths in children from measles virus infection by 50 percent.

Cebu is an island province in the Philippines, consisting of the island itself and 167 surrounding islands. Its capital is Cebu City, the oldest city in the Philippines, which forms part of the Cebu Metropolitan Area together with 4 neighbouring cities (see map at http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cebu). - Mod.CP]

