[9] Russia (Khakassia)
Date: Tue 24 Jun 2014
Source: 19Rus.info [in Russian, summ., transl. - Mod.CP]
http://19rus.info/index.php/obshchestvo/item/13027-u-rebenka-iz-khakasii-podozrevayut-bolezn-kotoroj-ne-bylo-sem-let


Currently a suspected case of measles has been registered in Khakassia in a child 7 years old living in the Ust-Abakan area. According to the Rospotrebnadzor Khakassia press service, no measles cases have been recorded in the region since 2007. The sick child had been residing outside Khakassia in St. Petersburg for 2 weeks prior to illness, where the infection most likely happened. The child had not been vaccinated against measles on account of medical contraindications. Daily medical supervision was provided for all those in contact with the sick child.

Epidemiologists believe that the cases of measles importation into Russia originate from exposure in Thailand, China, Turkey and Indonesia -- countries which are traditionally visited by Russian tourists. Measles is more severe in adults than in children, and in adults 3 percent of measles cases are complicated by pneumonia, bronchitis, otitis media, sinusitis, encephalitis. Mortality in acute measles encephalitis may reach 10 percent.

Vaccination is the main weapon against measles. This is especially relevant for those who regularly travel to measles disadvantaged countries and regions of the Russian Federation.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail from HealthMap Alerts
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Khakassia Republic (also spelled Khakasia, Khakasiya, Khakassiya) is located in the south of Eastern Siberia, part of Siberian Federal District. The length of the republic territory from north to south is 400 km (about 250 miles), from west to east, 200 km (about 125 miles). The capital and administrative center of Khakassia is Abakan. Khakassia Republic's population is about 533 000 (2012); land area is 61 569 sq. km. A map showing the location of Khakassiyaa can be accessed at: http://russiatrek.org/khakassia-republic. - Mod.CP]

******
[10] Russia (ex Ukraine)
Date: Tue 24 Jun 2014
Source: ITAR-TASS [in Russian, summ., transl. - Mod.CP]
http://en.itar-tass.com/non-political/737490


A threat of a measles outbreak has been growing in Russia in connection with the arrival of refugees from Ukraine, said Anna Popova, head of the Federal Consumer Protection Service (Rospotrebnadzor) at a news conference on Tuesday, 24 Jun 2014. The level of vaccination against measles among Ukrainian refugees is 2-3 times lower than that of the optimal 95 percent.

The refugees, like Russian citizens, should have been vaccinated against measles and poliomyelitis free of charge, Popova said. A maximum rate of vaccination of Russian citizens and refugees from Ukraine will be ensured in areas where refugees arrive. The dates for vaccination will be set for each particular region, Popova said.

[Byline: Dmitry Rogulin]

